snippet.textDisplay: Hey car people, I have an important question. I have a really hard time driving at night, not if its clear weather as much, but especially if the roads are wet. I have really light colored eyes and the lights really hinder my ability to see as well and not being able to focus on the lines gives me wicked anxiety. I noticed when riding passenger in a left hand drive car, I can see much better. Would it be worth finding a chassis with right hand drive not only cause its fun, but for the night driving aspect. Id be by the white line here in America. Any tips to help me drive my left hand drive at night until then would be appreciated too!

snippet.textDisplay: Looks like evo is well balanced. In couple semi-fast corners has more understeering as well as it looks on chicanes it is also a bit hesitant to turn.    Couple things that helped me: playing with toe in front to compensate chicanes also camber in rear and front. Changing it in just 0.1 degree might change the game. This means need to have more seat time to find ideal setup for you. Tire pressure: not sure from video but monitor pressure more frequently. Stint of two hotlaps, back to pits monitor pressure and repeat. That is my amateur advice. Keep pushing!

snippet.textDisplay: I would say the brake fluid is getting hot i dont think its the pads. but there can be a chance the rotors are getting to hot as well might want to think about modding some ducting or more ducking to get air to the rotors. Breaks work from transferring a spinning energy into heat energy then to rotor acts like a heat sink to dissipate the heat. And if you can get them if your going to push the car on a track slotted and drilled rotors will help more. make more noise but the drill holes will help prevent over gas when the pads get hot

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like you're driving it too much like a rwd car. you need to toss it into the corner a bit more, trail brake and get some rotation and then be full throttle before the apex with a good slip angle to point you out of the corner. I suggest going to do a beginner rally driving course, they will break you in and show you some techniques. Driving AWD at the track is very similar to rally style driving which is where I began racing.
If you are getting corner entry understeer then you can put some negative toe on the front, making sure rear toe is still positive. If you are getting understeer mid corner then you want toe in on the front. obviously more front camber would be better in both cases depending on tire temps and tire wear. positive rake will also help the rear rotate and give more front end grip. a softer rear swaybar or stiffer rear will reduce understeer. and stiffer front springs will also reduce understeer that isnt caused by uneven or rough surfaces.
But other than those simple setup requirements an Evo takes a different style of driving to get right, especially the evo 6 and below with no assisted yaw control. Trail braking, whether its to put weight on the fronts to help initial turn in, or to prevent mid corner understeer you want to rotate the rear before corner entry and get on the gas. A car slightly slipping but pointing in the right direction will be faster than a car with full grip but having to be dragged around the corner when it's trying to go straight.
I have a few good articles that may help you if you feel like reading pages and pages of pure knowledge.
